[3] Philippines: resurgence
Date: Sat 14 Aug 2021
Source: al Jazeera [edited]
https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/8/14/covid-19-resurgence-puts-philippine-medical-workers-under-strain


The Philippines's already stretched healthcare system is under more strain as the country reports its 2nd-largest daily increase in COVID-19 infections since the pandemic, providing more evidence of how the virulent delta variant may be spreading.

Hundreds of hospitals in the country were again nearing full capacity as of Saturday [14 Aug 2021], with some facilities reporting they had run out of intensive care unit beds for COVID-19 patients, leaving healthcare workers, who are forced to work longer hours, exhausted.

Despite an existing lockdown in Metro Manila, some neighbourhoods were placed under an even stricter quarantine order on Saturday [14 Aug 2021] as cases continue to rise.

"Usually the nurse-to-patient ratio in wards is 1:5, but we are handling up to 12 patients," said Maria Caridad delos Reyes, a staff nurse at the Philippine General Hospital, whose 8-hour shift now sometimes extends to 16 hours. "We're supposed to have a break time, but because we are extremely busy, we miss our meals, especially now that we are attending to moderate-to-severe COVID-19 patients," Delos Reyes told the Reuters news agency on Friday [13 Aug 2021].

The Lung Center of the Philippines in Metro Manila also reported that they are opening treatment stations using container vans placed in the hospital's parking lot to accommodate more COVID-19 patients.

Another hospital in the nearby province of Bulacan used its lobby as a triage area as their rooms are already at full capacity.

The health ministry recorded 13 177 new coronavirus infections on Friday [13 Aug 2021], the highest since a record daily tally of 15 310 on 2 Apr [2021], bringing total cases to 1.71 million, the 2nd-highest in Southeast Asia after Indonesia.

An increasing number of children have also been reported to have fallen sick due to the virus.

In Quezon City in Metro Manila, the government said 318 of the COVID-19 cases recorded between 1 and 7 Aug [2021] were children aged 17 and below, according to the Philippine Daily Inquirer on Sat.

The Manila capital region, an urban sprawl of 16 cities that is home to 13 million people, returned to a strict lockdown since 6 Aug [2021] to contain the spread of Delta, while the government tries to speed up its vaccination.

It would take 2-3 weeks before the effect of the lockdown is felt, health ministry spokesperson Maria Rosario Vergeire told a media briefing, as she urged the public to get vaccinated and follow health protocols.

There have been reports of a possible extension of the lockdown, which is currently scheduled only until 20 Aug [2021].

With about 11% of the country's 110 million people fully immunised, millions remain highly vulnerable to COVID-19, which has killed more than 29 800 in the Southeast Asian country.

According to the Herd Immunity PH vaccine tracker, it could take at least 7 more months, or until March 2022, for the government to reach its goal of immunising at least 70% of the country's adult population to reach herd immunity, months behind the target.

At a drive-through vaccination site in Manila, a 62-year-old cycle rickshaw driver, [RS], was thankful for getting a shot. "I hope this will help us with our lives. We haven't been able to move freely in so long, so this vaccination is a blessing," [RS] said.

According to the government's vaccination task force, almost 50% of Metro Manila's residents will be fully vaccinated by 20 Aug [2021], when the 2-week lockdown expires.

Vaccination implementer Vince Dizon told state TV that the target will be reached in the coming days. He also said that the government has hit or exceeded the 500 000 daily vaccinations nationwide.

The Philippines also announced on Friday [13 Aug 2021] it will extend a ban on travellers from India and 9 other countries to the end of August [2021] to try to contain Delta.

